text: In contrast to Kyiv, Chernihiv and even Sumy, Kharkiv is unfortunately situated only 40 kilometres away from the Russian border. That’s why even when the occupiers were pushed back, the war was far from over for Kharkiv.

text: A scarred city\nIf you spend some time looking at the Derzhprom building in Kharkiv, it might seem that the war never happened. [This is a building in central Kharkiv known as the State Industry Building or the Palace of Industry in English.
context_annotations: [{"domain": {"id": "123", "name": "Ongoing News Story", "description": "Ongoing News Stories like 'Brexit'"}, "entity": {"id": "1484601166080081920", "name": "Russo-Ukrainian conflict"}}]

text: The pavements are swept, the grass has been cut neatly, the trees are carefully pruned. But the moment you look back, the war becomes plainly obvious as the building of the Kharkiv Oblast Administration, destroyed by several Russian missile strikes, comes into view. https://t.co/yS6ks1oC1G

text: Test collapse: Balakliia and Kharkiv\nWe are meeting Oleh Syniehubov, the Head of Kharkiv Oblast State Administration, at 8 am on a central square near the Derzhprom building. He has agreed to take us with him to Balakliia, liberated a few days before.
context_annotations: [{"domain": {"id": "123", "name": "Ongoing News Story", "description": "Ongoing News Stories like 'Brexit'"}, "entity": {"id": "1484601166080081920", "name": "Russo-Ukrainian conflict"}}]

text: The satnav shows the nearest route and approximate journey time - 1 hour 20 minutes. It actually takes more than three hours one-way due to exploded bridges, damaged roads, and detours through fields or swamps. https://t.co/VEtPNw8UGu
author.name: Ukrainska Pravda in English
author.description: Official English page of Ukrainian media outlet “Ukrainska Pravda” 🇺🇦

text: "But even Kharkiv is in a bad way at the moment. I’m mostly talking about critical infrastructure facilities. The enemy targets them deliberately. The Russians are trying to hit sewage treatment facilities in Kharkiv. This is a very bad sign."
context_annotations: [{"domain": {"id": "123", "name": "Ongoing News Story", "description": "Ongoing News Stories like 'Brexit'"}, "entity": {"id": "1484601166080081920", "name": "Russo-Ukrainian conflict"}}]

author.description: Official English page of Ukrainian media outlet “Ukrainska Pravda” 🇺🇦

text: And what he says about Kharkiv sounds especially vivid and disturbing against the backdrop of a weary, somewhat irritated group of people waiting for humanitarian aid. https://t.co/S8GuMSSsVX
context_annotations: [{"domain": {"id": "123", "name": "Ongoing News Story", "description": "Ongoing News Stories like 'Brexit'"}, "entity": {"id": "1484601166080081920", "name": "Russo-Ukrainian conflict"}}]

text: The city has already had several opportunities to "rehearse" the apocalyptic scenario, though only briefly, no longer than half a day at a time. That’s how long it usually takes municipal service workers to restore the power supply.
